Show HN: Jsonnet Training
text:
Hi HN! I'm usually a lurker, but I thought I'd share the first video of an online Jsonnet training I'm working on to get your feedback. It is the introduction to the training showing why Jsonnet is interesting and why you should probably have it in your toolbox. The link of this Show HN is a blog post embedding the video. If the blog is down, you can access the video directly on youtube at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W8kFrUOpO7s

I plan to make the whole training available on Udemy, but if you have advices regarding this, I'm also interested.

Thanks in advance for your constructive feedback as it is my first foray in online training and even online content production. For the curious, I created the content with OBS and edited it with Kdenlive.

Show HN: Generative AI – Short and Sweet – Perpetual Views/ Videos
text:
The 7th episode of the newsletter Generative AI - Short & Sweet is out now. --> https://generativeai.net/newsletter

Perpetual View/Video Generation (PVG). AI models generate open-ended videos from one image only - at least that’s the newest approach from Google Research [1]. These videos are “flying“ through a scene depicted in the input image. The range of potential applications is endless. Further, the tech behind it is incredibly smart and it marks the next cornerstone of generative AI.

In this episode we talk about the PVG's tech side and brainstorm about its future applications. (+ a little digression about the future usage of synthetic data in AI training.)

Best, Martin

Ask HN: How do you use computers faster?
text:
I noticed something weird today by websearching "world's fastest computer user". I had to search "fast computer use", "how to interface computers faster", and a few others.

There appears to be absolutely nothing mainstream about the slowest part of the computer experience: the users.

This leaves me with so many questions:

* why does everyone want computers to be faster when their sludgy brains are the weak point in the process? * how DO you get faster at computers? my theory is that the faster you are, the more you get done, so what does it take? * how come FAMGA isn't on this beyond brain interfacing? isn't there an easier way that uses present technology and just a teensy bit of education?

Not really sure where I'm going with this, but just wanted to throw that idea here.
